messages.message: Uploaded patch set 3: Patch Set 2 was rebased.

Patch Set 3:

As discussed in https://codereview.qt-project.org/c/qt/qtbase/+/346604 , I am introducing the two new signals flagsAboutToBeChanged() and flagsChanged() to QAbstractItemModel.
Uploaded patch set 4: Patch Set 3 was rebased.
Uploaded patch set 5: Patch Set 4 was rebased.

Patch Set 5:

I know you already committed a bunch of changes to implement this but isn't it more straightforward to finally admit flags is part of data (as it is already in QStandardItemModel) and just crate a public Qt::FlagRole and use the existing pipeline already in place for dataChanged instead of building it from scratch? I get that flags could return valid with an invalid index input but I don't see this being a problem at all

Patch Set 5:

> Patch Set 5:
> 
> I know you already committed a bunch of changes to implement this but isn't it more straightforward to finally admit flags is part of data (as it is already in QStandardItemModel) and just crate a public Qt::FlagRole and use the existing pipeline already in place for dataChanged instead of building it from scratch? I get that flags could return valid with an invalid index input but I don't see this being a problem at all

Ok, I see the error of may ways (we'd need a dataAboutToBeChanged signal and that opens a can of worms), ignore me

subject: WIP: Add API support for cross-platform dark mode

values.-1: I would prefer this is not merged as is
values.+1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

messages.message:
Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2 Sanity-Review+1

Apparently pushing a Work In Progress

Patch Set 1:

RFC .. does that make sense to have sth for platforms like WebAssembly, etc?

Can be tested on linux by sth like https://paste.ubuntu.com/p/vYBkrSpwzR/ 

Ofc , the default dark palette needs to be fleshed out, do we have any experts?

Patch Set 1:

I think if we're going to expose something like this in a cross platform manner it should overlap with as many platforms as possible. Which means possibly exposing only a subset of the various options. More and more platforms have a "dark" mode now, but I'm not sure the "night" one makes sense. macOS also has high contrast and vibrant versions which wouldn't be so easy to add in a cross platform manner:

https://developer.apple.com/documentation/appkit/nsappearancename?language=objc

In web-land the CSS approach includes just light and dark:

https://drafts.csswg.org/mediaqueries-5/#descdef-media-prefers-color-scheme

There's also stuff in there to separate high contrast from normal contrast, perhaps we could do the same.

Since we may end up with more modes than one I think app attributes is not the way to go, we should probably expose it as a real property.

One thing to keep in mind is that on macOS this appearance can be set on a per window level as well, forcing only one window to be dark. 

We should also consider this feature in relation to a generic non-widget styling/theme API, as well as the existing style/theme APIs we have in Qt, QStyleHints, etc.

Patch Set 1:

Hm..ok..seems we cannot really achieve a good cross-platform API for that...

Patch Set 1:

At the very least we need a way to detect which system theme is in use:

https://codereview.qt-project.org/c/qt/qtbase/+/357256/1#message-c47758d2d465e8be14f7a91f0cb4e7c01fbef465

Patch Set 1:

btw, I started working on a similar feature in KDE: https://invent.kde.org/frameworks/kguiaddons/-/merge_requests/27

For Linux the relevant API would be the one introduced in https://github.com/flatpak/xdg-desktop-portal/pull/633

messages.message:
Patch Set 1:

I do not understand this.
If a function is private or static, compiler checks if it is used, and if it cannot find the use it complains. It should have nothing to do with the name.
Either make it public/exported if it is used from outside, or add a Q_UNUSED(function) somewhere to ensure it is always seen as used, if you want to always emit it

Patch Set 1:

I can see it being used, yet the compiler tells it's unused. Changing the name seems to help somehow. Maybe it's a symptom of something else e.g.:

the caller of url() is not called itself, so the compiler figures that url() is also unused and warns so. that doesn't explain how changing the name helps. maybe the name is ambiguous (yet I would've expected a full-blown error in that case).

Patch Set 1:

Yeah, can confirm that clang reports "url()" to be an unused function while "q_qmltc_docUrl()" to be a used function (or at least there's no warning in that case).
There are no other changes in the generator, reproducible for me with https://codereview.qt-project.org/c/qt/qtdeclarative/+/387502/2 when compiling ComponentType.qml.

Patch Set 3:

> Patch Set 3:
> 
> There's one weird case I haven't covered:
> 
> // x property with NOTIFY xSignal
> Type {
>   onXChanged: { console.log("one"); }
>   onXSignal: { console.log("two"); }
> }
> 
> running such code with QQmlComponent would produce two messages: "one" and "two" (maybe in reverse order though)
> 
> qmllint for now just considers it fine as well, but should we just reject it instead?

We shouldn't outright reject that code. We can issue a warning, however that should be a different change.

I think the established way to do this is to inherit the core event dispatcher, and then override processPostedEvents. See e.g. bool QIOSEventDispatcher::processPostedEvents()

Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Based on earlier comment

Patch Set 2:

> Patch Set 2:
> 
> I think the established way to do this is to inherit the core event dispatcher, and then override processPostedEvents. See e.g. bool QIOSEventDispatcher::processPostedEvents()

Looks like that's QEventDispatcherCoreFoundation::processPostedEvents() though, so iOS/Mac only.

We could unify the API in a follow-up though, either by renaming one of them or move processPostedEvents() up to QAbstractEventDispatcher.

messages.message:
Patch Set 1:

Hi. This patch is a result of a discussion in the previous patch of the chain. Please have a look.
Uploaded patch set 2: Patch Set 1 was rebased.

Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

To me this seems a sensible change.

Please remove this line:
https://code.qt.io/cgit/qt/qtconnectivity.git/tree/src/bluetooth/qbluetoothdevicediscoveryagent_darwin.mm#n151

Otherwise there will be an assert if BT is switched OFF and user tries to call start() again.

A separate thing from this patch: on macOS it is enough to switch OFF the bluetooth to get the "InvalidAdapterError". There is no way to recover from that without restarting the application because the check is done at the controller constructor time. This is pre-existing and should be fixed in another patch imo.

Patch Set 3:

> Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1
> 
> To me this seems a sensible change.
> 
> Please remove this line:
> https://code.qt.io/cgit/qt/qtconnectivity.git/tree/src/bluetooth/qbluetoothdevicediscoveryagent_darwin.mm#n151
> 
> Otherwise there will be an assert if BT is switched OFF and user tries to call start() again.

Done.

> A separate thing from this patch: on macOS it is enough to switch OFF the bluetooth to get the "InvalidAdapterError". There is no way to recover from that without restarting the application because the check is done at the controller constructor time. This is pre-existing and should be fixed in another patch imo.

Your contribution is welcome here :) Hard for me to deal with Darwin code, as I can't even compile it locally.
But generally there is no need to fix it now, when we removed the check. Or am I missing smth?

Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

> Patch Set 3:
> 
> > Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1
> > 
> > To me this seems a sensible change.
> > 
> > Please remove this line:
> > https://code.qt.io/cgit/qt/qtconnectivity.git/tree/src/bluetooth/qbluetoothdevicediscoveryagent_darwin.mm#n151
> > 
> > Otherwise there will be an assert if BT is switched OFF and user tries to call start() again.
> 
> Done.
> 
> > A separate thing from this patch: on macOS it is enough to switch OFF the bluetooth to get the "InvalidAdapterError". There is no way to recover from that without restarting the application because the check is done at the controller constructor time. This is pre-existing and should be fixed in another patch imo.

Thanks, now works fine on macOS too.

> Your contribution is welcome here :) Hard for me to deal with Darwin code, as I can't even compile it locally.
> But generally there is no need to fix it now, when we removed the check. Or am I missing smth?

I also think it will be a separate commit, I created a Jira task for myself so I don't forget:
https://bugreports.qt.io/browse/QTBUG-99288

Patch looks good. Thanks.
